{"cursor":"10307","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Carolyn R. Bertozzi image = Carolyn Bertozzi IMG 9384.jpg image_size =\n| 240px alt = caption = birth_date = birth_place = Boston, Massachusetts\n| death_date =  death_place = residence =\n| citizenship = nationality = fields = chemistry workplaces = University of\n| California, Berkeley Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory University of\n| California, San Francisco alma_mater = Harvard University University of\n| California, Berkeley University of California, San Francisco\n| doctoral_advisor = academic_advisors = doctoral_students = notable_students =\n| known_for = bioorthogonal chemistry author_abbrev_bot = author_abbrev_zoo =\n| influences = influenced = awards = MacArthur Foundation Fellowship (1999) Lemelson-\n| MIT Prize (2010) signature =  signature_alt = footnotes\n| = spouse =\n}} 'Carolyn Ruth Bertozzi' (born May 19, 1966) is an American chemist. She is\nthe T.Z. and Irmgard Chu Distinguished Professor of Chemistry and Professor of\nMolecular and Cell Biology at the University of California, Berkeley; Professor\nof Molecular and Cellular Pharmacology at the University of California, San\nFrancisco; is an Investigator of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute;\nand is the former Director of the Molecular Foundry, a nanoscience research\ncenter at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. She\nreceived a MacArthur \"genius\" award at age 33, [http://www.macfound.org/sit-\ne/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.1142725/k.2948/Fellows_List__July_1999.htm Fellows List (July\n1999)], MacArthur Foundation. making her one of the youngest scientists to\nreceive this award. In 2010 she was the first woman to receive the prestigious\nLemelson-MIT Prize faculty award. She is a member of the National Academy of\nSciences and the Institute of Medicine.\n","linknr":252,"url":"Carolyn_R._Bertozzi","recorded":1376421884,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Carolyn_R._Bertozzi&action=edit","/w/index.php?ti